With almost 5000 reviews and still being 4 starts this was a definite must do on my last trip to San Francisco. I really wanted to give this place 5 stars, I really did. Went there and thankfully the line wasn't very long. By reading the reviews we knew that we definitely wanted the banana creme pie and a morning bun. The problem was we had no clue what else to get. After checking out the case full of treats my gf and I were having even more trouble deciding. We made the mistake of asking the guy taking our order for a recommendation. He rolls his eyes and moves away. He comes back and we ask for a croque and he said they wouldn't be ready for 15 minutes. We asked if we could go ahead and order it and get it when they are ready and he gave us a definite "NO". Soooo we looked in the case for some more breakfast eats and tried to pick out what looked good. We get to the cash register as the girl for recommendation and she is rude too! She rolls her eyes, just like the first guy that took our order did and kind of throws her hands towards the case and says to pick something out we like. Super rude. We asked how the quiche was and she says its good if you like chard and mushrooms. After we get all the rudeness our of the way, or so we thought, we say that we had ordered the morning bun, bread pudding, chard/mushroom quiche, and the banana cream pie. The cashier then tells us that they will bring the banana cream pie out to us when it is ready and gives us a number for the table. WAIT....didn't they first guy tell us they can't do that for the croque?????? WTF is up??? Anyway we pay, have a seat outside and being to eat. On to the food. I must say for all the hype I was not very impressed at all. I am from the South so I've had my share of bread puddings. The one I got from here wasn't bad but it definitely wasn't great either. The morning bun that everyone raves about was just a cinnamon roll without the icing on it. In fact it was kind of dry for my taste. Once again, maybe I'm used to being in the south with sticky buns that are soft and gooey. The quiche was ok. The crust was tasty but overall it wasn't amazing as I would have expected. The one saving grace was the banana cream pie. The crust was delicious, lined with chocolate on the inside, bananas, tasty creme topping and chocolate shavings to top it off. We had this with our lunch a few hours later and it was very good. Just because you know (or hope) that your product is good is no excuse for your servers being rude. Maybe the food was excellent and I am just being bias but the RUDE SERVICE completely ruined this visit to Tartine for me. The service was so poor I don't think I would consider going back here.

Very delicious food and baked goods, but this place is very tight and busy. If it's raining, grab a seat ASAP because there aren't many tables and people tend to eat their scones one tiny bite at a time. The food is pretty expensive for what it is, simple baked goods. Also, you are supposed to bus your own table, so you can decide if you'd like to tip or not. If you don't bus, you can pretty much assume the next customer who has been patiently waiting is going to do it for you. I'd give this place a 3 1/2 if I could do half rating. Prob best to grab and go if you can!

It's five stars for sure, except for the price. But considering the quality, the prices are not unreasonable. Tartine is definitely a place where certain things are really good, and other items are just overrated. I'll just give a short list of the stuff I love, and that should steer you in the right direction. Chocolate Souffle Cake - Prepare to drink a lot of milk with this, because it's super chocolatey and decadent. I really enjoy the unapologetically intense chocolate flavor and its incredible richness. Its flavor and texture demand your attention. This cake isn't for everyone, but I really like it. Country Loaf - It's hard to beat a fresh, hot from the oven country loaf. The crust is really hearty and crunchy, while the inside has a soft and glutinous texture. The elasticity makes it really fun to eat. I also really like how it's not too sour. I'm not a fan of really sour sourdough, and Tartine knows how to strike a good balance. It's just sour enough to tickle your tongue. Try to eat as much of it as you can on the first day, because it dries out fast and becomes exponentially worse overnight. Plain Croissants - The crust on the plain croissants is amazing. They way they roll them gives the croissants a really nice vertical layer of crust. All the little crispy layers crescendo into a big satisfying crunch. The flavor is rich and full of butter, so I understand if people think it's too heavy. The texture is also more dense and bready, kinda like brioche or something. If that bothers you, then you probably won't like their croissants. I don't really get the obsession with their bread pudding. I think it's way too eggy.

I had my first Tartine encounter today; and it lived up to every good word that's been written here. My friends and I jumped on the Muni and headed to the world famous bakery for breakfast on our last morning in the city by the bay. I had lots of images in my mind from all the food porn I've seen in the Tartine coffee table books. I was delighted to see it looks just as beautiful in person. I resisted the urge to press my face up against the glass and softly weep. There's nothing I love on this planet in quite the way I love a hot ham and cheese croissants, and this has to be the patron saint of hot ham and cheese croissants. It was so flaky, not greasy, the cheese was warm but not totally melted and the ham just a tiny bit crispy. Every bite was perfect as I took my time with each flaky layer. The latte was also great, and I especially love that it is $4 even. It was warm enough to sit outside, I met the nicest couple and their two little greyhounds, discovered that this particular block of Guerrero happens to also be the mecca of darling (and adorably dressed) children, and to top it off, I had lovely company! What a perfect start to the last day of a wonderful visit. It's a good life guys. Croissants from Tartine certainly don't hurt. xo

I remember a time when I used to just walk in to Tartine, grab whatever I wanted and take it to go to Dolores Park and just pig out. Everyone behind the counter was friendly and beautiful and the sun shone like a glass of OJ that mom just poured. This memory has probably be colored by time and distance--as the internet says: 'Only 90's kids will remember' ... I digress. Tartine is undoubtedly a top-notch joint, with a spread that rivals the dinner parties of the Romans for its opulence, quality, and presentation, and everything on offer is amazing. Buying one of everything (the obvious impulse when confronted with a stacked pastry case and lines that make make you wonder if the future of food scarcity isn't closer that you imagined) will not only skew your BMI for the next two months, but bankrupt you over time, so let me be your Tartine Virgil: Croque Monsieur - A huge (big enough for two--or three) open-faced sandwich with melty gruyere, creamy bÃ©chamel and crispy ham. Comes with a pair of Tartine's home-marinated spice carrots to cut the richness fatigue if you're planning to demolish it in one sitting. Brioche Bread Pudding w/ Fruit - Delicious, carby pudding with heaping helpings of fresh fruit on top. Protip: get the big bowl. Warning: ONLY PURCHASE IF HOT. Gougere - AKA Gruyere Puff. Egg dough, cheese and a little thyme inflated by the breath of angels into a spectacularly delicious ball of featherlight softness and heavenly light. Morning Bun - It's a hypebeast, but damned if it isn't the best morning bun in all of California. Crispy and sweet on the outside, soft and smushy on the inside, just like grandma. Honorable mention: Banana creme pie tart, pan au chocolate, frangipane, everything else.

Ah. Tartine. Back down to 4 stars for you. MORNING BUN, I still love you. You were a bit burnt on top, and I should have ordered you warmed (or I waited too long to eat you). BANANA CREAM TART, I fell in love with you. $7 for a 4" flaky pastry coated in dark chocolate and lined with caramel, topped with pastry cream glopped on top of lightly sweetened cream enveloping fresh banana chunks (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/tartine-bakery-and-cafe-san-francisco?select=ayxuXDGK1Rf3QPqveL9uXQ#-rbf54OjrrOM137u_QS_5A). If you love bananas, you will go bananas for this dessert. And if you really wanna demonstrate how bananas you are for bananas, you can get a 9" that serves 8 for $45. The pastry cream is light and pairs wonderfully with the generous banana cream filling that is chock full of ripe banana slices (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/tartine-bakery-and-cafe-san-francisco?select=ayxuXDGK1Rf3QPqveL9uXQ#msFkNyQNZX5alN2RJ6-jXQ). The flaky pastry crust is sublime, and the chocolate lining is the cherry on top. The dark chocolate shavings on top are very dark--the bitterness initially took me aback. But the entire combination was so mind-blowing that I couldn't help but devour the entire tart in one sitting by myself. Well, my friends were too preoccupied in their attempt to consume their horrid bread pudding. So I really was left with no choice to self-induce a sugar-rush headache. Funsies. Not. But, regardless, you are worth $7 (and should be shared). BREAD PUDDING, I HATE YOU. Both times I have ordered you, you have utterly disappointed me. Yes, it's kinda cool that you have different fruits and stuff. But that doesn't make up for the fact that the first time I ate you in the $4 cup serving, you were burnt (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/tartine-bakery-and-cafe-san-francisco?select=RIfVl39QsG2ccMAAO_gzcQ#RIfVl39QsG2ccMAAO_gzcQ). When my friends ordered you in the $6.75 bowl serving, you were swimming in soup (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/tartine-bakery-and-cafe-san-francisco?filter_by_userid=True&select=5B4igFQIDJA2Y0hp9zwcBQ&userid=sPqHcRC--tRanPC-g4pNwQ#5B4igFQIDJA2Y0hp9zwcBQ). Soppy, soggy, SAD! They like bread pudding, at least more than I do. But they did not like you. You were left largely uneaten, left to drown in your own puddle of dismal, drenching despair.     I remember a time when I used to just walk in to Tartine, grab whatever I wanted and take it to go to Dolores Park and just pig out. Everyone behind the counter was friendly and beautiful and the sun shone like a glass of OJ that mom just poured. This memory has probably be colored by time and distance--as the internet says: 'Only 90's kids will remember' ... I digress.

    Tartine is undoubtedly a top-notch joint, with a spread that rivals the dinner parties of the Romans for its opulence, quality, and presentation, and everything on offer is amazing. Buying one of everything (the obvious impulse when confronted with a stacked pastry case and lines that make make you wonder if the future of food scarcity isn't closer that you imagined) will not only skew your BMI for the next two months, but bankrupt you over time, so let me be your Tartine Virgil:

    Croque Monsieur - A huge (big enough for two--or three) open-faced sandwich with melty gruyere, creamy bÃ©chamel and crispy ham. Comes with a pair of Tartine's home-marinated spice carrots to cut the richness fatigue if you're planning to demolish it in one sitting.

    Brioche Bread Pudding w/ Fruit - Delicious, carby pudding with heaping helpings of fresh fruit on top. Protip: get the big bowl. Warning: ONLY PURCHASE IF HOT.

    Gougere - AKA Gruyere Puff. Egg dough, cheese and a little thyme inflated by the breath of angels into a spectacularly delicious ball of featherlight softness and heavenly light.

    Morning Bun - It's a hypebeast, but damned if it isn't the best morning bun in all of California. Crispy and sweet on the outside, soft and smushy on the inside, just like grandma.

    Honorable mention: Banana creme pie tart, pan au chocolate, frangipane, everything else.

    I can see why people are willing to wait in line at this super small bakery. They specialize in baked goods and they're great at it!

    Waited in line for about 10 minutes. It didn't seem long. However, when I arrived inside and saw their display case, I was sort of overwhelmed! I wish they had a stand outside with their menus for customers to decide on things to order while in line.

    My friend has heard great things about their bread pudding (flavor is seasonal) so we opted to order one of those. We also got a rocher with toasted almonds, and the breakfast bun. All three were super delicious and if I wasn't so full, I would have gotten right back in line and ordered a couple more for the road.

    The Bread Pudding we had was apple. It had a lot of steamed egg, and sweetness from the apples. The bread itself was moist and melted in your mouth.

    Roccier with toasted almonds was light on the outside but slightly sticky and crunchy on the inside from the caramel and almonds. The portion size was perfect and would go well with some black tea or coffee.

    The breakfast bun was a cinnamon sugar covered piece of heaven. It was light, fluffy, and was bigger than my fist! I would def recommend this to anyone who comes here. Its slightly messy because crumbs of cinnamon sugar are always falling off, but I think that being messy makes eating a lot more fun.

    As for the service, we asked some questions and the girls behind the counter very helpful.

    Good luck trying to get a table here. In the whole cafe, there is probably only 7 tables and people like to take their time chatting and drinking their coffee here. I would def take my orders to go as it gets super crowded, loud and hard to walk around.

    Ah. Tartine. Back down to 4 stars for you.

    MORNING BUN, I still love you. You were a bit burnt on top, and I should have ordered you warmed (or I waited too long to eat you). But you are still the same combination of crispy, flaky orange cinnamon glaze surrounding soft chewy dough that I fell for back in 2013 (yelp.com/biz_photos/tartâ€¦). You are worth $3.95. Okay, well, I wish you were $2 or $3.

    BANANA CREAM TART, I fell in love with you. $7 for a 4" flaky pastry coated in dark chocolate and lined with caramel, topped with pastry cream glopped on top of lightly sweetened cream enveloping fresh banana chunks (yelp.com/biz_photos/tartâ€¦). If you love bananas, you will go bananas for this dessert. And if you really wanna demonstrate how bananas you are for bananas, you can get a 9" that serves 8 for $45. The pastry cream is light and pairs wonderfully with the generous banana cream filling that is chock full of ripe banana slices (yelp.com/biz_photos/tartâ€¦). The flaky pastry crust is sublime, and the chocolate lining is the cherry on top. The dark chocolate shavings on top are very dark--the bitterness initially took me aback. But the entire combination was so mind-blowing that I couldn't help but devour the entire tart in one sitting by myself. Well, my friends were too preoccupied in their attempt to consume their horrid bread pudding. So I really was left with no choice to self-induce a sugar-rush headache. Funsies. Not. But, regardless, you are worth $7 (and should be shared).

    BREAD PUDDING, I HATE YOU. Both times I have ordered you, you have utterly disappointed me. Yes, it's kinda cool that you have different fruits and stuff. But that doesn't make up for the fact that the first time I ate you in the $4 cup serving, you were burnt (yelp.com/biz_photos/tartâ€¦). When my friends ordered you in the $6.75 bowl serving, you were swimming in soup (yelp.com/biz_photos/tartâ€¦). Soppy, soggy, SAD! They like bread pudding, at least more than I do. But they did not like you. You were left largely uneaten, left to drown in your own puddle of dismal, drenching despair. I should've gotten the hint when the guy running the cash register remarked, "Wow, the bread pudding is super wet this time." My naÃ¯ve self didn't know any better. I should have asked for a different scoop of you. But my friends were too nice to let me go complain. Darn you, bread pudding. You are not worth $4 or $6.75. Never again will I choose you.

    Yes morning bun. Yes banana cream tart (wow that is the 9th time I've used "banana" in this review...now 10th). NO BREAD PUDDING.

    Enjoyed the food and the atmosphere but not the lines.

    Actually, we got there around 3 PM, so the line for food wasn't that intimidating. It snaked around half the store but moved quick. What I'm complaining about is the single bathroom in the back, which had a shorter yet longer-wait line for it. Those girls in front of me were taking their sweeeeeet time.

    After reading Yelp reviews, I had my mind set on a morning bun. But the downside of arriving at 3 PM is that they'll probably run out of their most popular item. I asked the lady for a time estimate of depletion, and she said they usually run out around 1 - 1:30 PM. In its place I ordered the BREAD PUDDING in a cup for $4, total was $4.34.

    The bread pudding (yelp.com/biz_photos/tartâ€¦) was pretty good. But it was burnt on top! Is that normal? In any case, I discovered that bread pudding wasn't my favorite dessert item because of its texture--it's
    incredibly mushy for my tastes (I guess it really is a bread-pudding, but to me it was like eating sweetly soggy bread with a burnt top, which clashed even more). By nature, the bread was very moist, and the seasonal fruit of cinnamon apples were sweet, perhaps too sweet given the sweetness of the bread. This was my first time eating bread pudding, and although I don't like it, I figured that this would be the best place for me to have tried it.

    My friends ordered the TRES LECHES CAKE slice, which was subtly sweet! It's soaked in 3 types of milk, which surprisingly gave it a slight coffee undertone. It too is very mushy but not so much as the bread pudding. I loved the layers of the cake, especially the top layer. They also ordered the LEMON MERINGUE CAKE slice, which had too much of both extremes: sharply sweet and sour. I enjoyed the moistness of it though, along with the cream on top.

    Aside from the bakery items, we experienced the ordeal of some crazy ladies who demanded that my friend to save their spots at the table while they stood in line... No thanks.

    I will more likely than not drag another friend to come back with me so as to give the morning bun, ham and cheese croissant, and the banana cream tart fair shots!
